Admin install AdblockPlus for Firefox

A guide for the system-wide installation of the Adblock Plus extension for Mozilla Firefox under Microsoft Windows.

Download the XPI file

Extensions for Mozilla Firefox are shipped as Cross-Platform Install ("XPInstall") files. Those are basically regular ZIP archives using the *.xpi file extension.

On the AdblockPlus for Firefox download-page, one can right-click the Add to Firefox button, select "Save Link As" in the context menu and choose a destination to save the XPI file to.

Convert to ZIP archive

After re-naming the extension archive from *.xpi to *.zip, one can easily access the contents, just like a regular directory.

Determine target directory

The installation directory or destination path is assembled according to the following pattern:

%firefox%\browser\extensions\%id%

Whilst %firefox% is the browser installation directory and %id% the developer ID of the extension's publisher. The following example assumes the Firefox installation to reside in C:\Program Files\Mozilla Firefox and uses the ID associated with the official Adblock Plus for Firefox release:

C:\Program Files\Mozilla Firefox\browser\extensions\{d10d0bf8-f5b5-c8b4-a8b2-2b9879e08c5d}

One could also refer to the install.rdf file in the ZIP archive's root, where the ID is stored in the <em:id/> element's content. Any XML or text editor should be sufficient.

Extract and install Adblock Plus

The actual installation process is pretty straigt-forward: The context-menu's Extract All option allows for the direct installation of the extension into the target directory determined in the former step.

Disable user confirmation

Although one could consider the installation complete by now, there is still room for improvement. Especially the circumstance that any user would get promptet to confirm the installation (when starting Firefox for the first time again). One can prevent this behavior in the configuration:

At first, one needs to ensure the %firefox%\browser\default\preferences directory being present (which may require creating it first). Afterwards, one can place the following one-liner in a *.js file there:

pref("extensions.autoDisableScopes", 0);

While this approach isn't considered optimal and could be improved, it should suit most requirements. Note, however, that this does not work for users who have started *Firefox* since the installation of Adblock Plus already, if any - those won't be prompted again.
